docs.abstract: The entertainment industry has undergone a tectonic shift in the past two years, but many of the most powerful people remain the same.
docs.snippet: The entertainment industry has undergone a tectonic shift in the past two years, but many of the most powerful people remain the same.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — In Hollywood, director jobs are no longer automatically filled by white men. Television writers’ rooms have made diversity and inclusion top priorities. Human resources departments at major media corporations are more responsive when complaints are filed. Intimacy coordinators, who introduce physical consent considerations into the artistic process, are now normal on productions featuring sexual content.

headline.main: Harvey Weinstein Is Gone, but Hollywood Is Still a Man’s World
headline.print_headline: Weinstein Is Gone, But Men Still Pull The Big Strings In Hollywood

docs.abstract: A start-up known for providing free credit scores, Credit Karma is set to avoid the I.P.O. market and instead sell to an established financial firm.
docs.snippet: A start-up known for providing free credit scores, Credit Karma is set to avoid the I.P.O. market and instead sell to an established financial firm.
docs.lead_paragraph: Intuit, the home of TurboTax and Mint, is nearing a deal to buy Credit Karma, a start-up that grew to fame by offering consumers free access to their credit scores, for about $7 billion in cash and stock, two people briefed on the matter said on Sunday.

headline.main: Intuit Is Expected to Buy Credit Karma in $7 Billion Deal
headline.print_headline: A Big Fish In Fintech Swallowing A Start-Up

docs.abstract: A new National Labor Relations Board rule scales back the responsibility of parent companies for violations by franchisees or contractors.
docs.snippet: A new National Labor Relations Board rule scales back the responsibility of parent companies for violations by franchisees or contractors.
docs.lead_paragraph: The National Labor Relations Board announced a new regulation on Tuesday that makes it harder to challenge companies over their labor practices, potentially affecting the rights of millions of workers.

headline.main: Franchise Workers Lose Some Power to Challenge Labor Practices
headline.print_headline: U.S. Labor Board Blunts Challenges To Parent Companies

docs.abstract: Responding to criticism that it was cutting into restaurant profits, the food-delivery giant said it was making a change to stop charging fees for calls that do not end with an order.
docs.snippet: Responding to criticism that it was cutting into restaurant profits, the food-delivery giant said it was making a change to stop charging fees for calls that do not end with an order.
docs.lead_paragraph: Facing mounting pressure from regulators and restaurant owners, the food-delivery giant Grubhub said on Thursday that it would revise its widely criticized phone-ordering system to avoid charging restaurants for calls that do not result in orders.

headline.main: Under Pressure, Grubhub Changes Its Ordering System
headline.print_headline: Grubhub Modifies Its Widely Criticized Phone-Ordering System

docs.abstract: Rural itinerant workers are being blocked from cities, kicked out of apartments and rejected by companies as the authorities impose strict controls to stem the spread of the virus.
docs.snippet: Rural itinerant workers are being blocked from cities, kicked out of apartments and rejected by companies as the authorities impose strict controls to stem the spread of the virus.
docs.lead_paragraph: Clutching a gray plastic suitcase filled with most of his belongings — a blanket, a toothbrush, a pair of white sneakers and a comb — Wang Sheng goes from factory to factory in southern China begging for a job. The answer is always no.

headline.main: Coronavirus Lockdowns Torment an Army of Poor Migrant Workers in China

docs.abstract: Battling a troubled move and loss of shoppers’ trust, the New York online grocery service now contends with increased competition.
docs.snippet: Battling a troubled move and loss of shoppers’ trust, the New York online grocery service now contends with increased competition.
docs.lead_paragraph: About a year and a half ago, longtime patrons of the pioneering grocery delivery service FreshDirect started complaining that orders were arriving hours late. There were broken eggs and spoiled fruit. One customer reported that she had paid $200 for groceries — only to receive nothing but seltzer and a loaf of bread.

headline.main: FreshDirect, After Broken Eggs and Angry Customers, Stages a Comeback
headline.print_headline: Can FreshDirect Reclaim Ground Lost to Amazon?
